My meme

The inspo meme is an image of a cat reading a newspaper with no text. In order for the meme to be altered text could be added or the original image can be altered (eg. by having the colors changed or a filter added).

library(magick)
library(tidyverse)

# Load the template meme
meme_url <- "https://i.kym-cdn.com/entries/icons/facebook/000/011/656/sophiscated_cat.jpg"
meme <- meme_url %>%
  image_read()

captions <- c("I should drop out and start a cult", "I can't read", "I hate my life", "I freaking love taxes", "My family doesnt respect me")

# obtain template width
meme_width <- image_info(meme)$width

#create a blank box for annotated text
blank_image <- image_blank(width = meme_width, height = 50, color = "#F0F0F0")

#add text to the blank box
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[1], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")

#append the box/text to the inspo meme
final_meme <- image_append(c(meme, annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)

#download the final meme
image_write(final_meme, paste0("meme.png"))

final_meme

library(magick)
library(tidyverse)

# Load the template meme
meme_url <- "https://i.kym-cdn.com/entries/icons/facebook/000/011/656/sophiscated_cat.jpg"
meme <- meme_url %>%
  image_read()

captions <- c("I should drop out and start a cult", "I can't read", "I hate my life", "I freaking love taxes", "My family doesnt respect me")

# obtain template width
meme_width <- image_info(meme)$width

#create a blank box for annotated text
blank_image <- image_blank(width = meme_width, height = 50, color = "#F0F0F0")


#create each frame of the meme for the animation (annotate the blank then append it to the template)
#frame 1
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[1], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")
frame1 <- image_append(c(meme, annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)

#frame 2
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[2], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")
frame2 <- image_append(c(image_blur(meme, 10, 5), annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)


#frame 3
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[3], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")
frame3 <- image_append(c(image_modulate(meme, brightness = 100, saturation = 400, hue = 190), annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)
frame3

#frame 4
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[4], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")
frame4 <- image_append(c(image_flip(meme), annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)


#frame 5
annotated_blank <- image_annotate(blank_image, captions[5], font = "Helvetica", size = 30, color = "#000000", gravity = "north")
frame5 <- image_append(c(image_charcoal(meme), annotated_blank), stack = TRUE)



#create a vector containing each frame (image)
all_memes <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4, frame5)

#download each frame as an image
for (i in 1:5) {
  image_write(all_memes[i], paste0("meme", i, ".png"))
}

#create an animation using each frame
animation <- image_animate(all_memes, fps = 1)

#download the animation as a gif
image_write(animation, "my_animated.gif")
Here is the animated meme

Creativity

One aspect of creativity I have done in this project is my use of for loops in my code which is a function that is not expected of us. Furthermore I used various magick functions that weren’t presented to us in class such as flip, modulate, charcoal and blur. On top of this I used the image_info function as well as doing $width in order to get the precise width of my inspo meme so that my text boxes would be of an equal width. I also demonstrated the ability to change the font and color of the text in said text boxes. Finally some of the functions have purpose in relation to the caption, for example the “I cant read” caption is paired with a blur indicating that the cat is blind.
